{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474958","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474958"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:27:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:27:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12473"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12473","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12473"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.47,0.01,0.01,0.49,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4980"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51143"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4980","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4980"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12473"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36403"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"152"},{"type":"tags","id":"1040"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1844"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"6376"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8240"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14554"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44127"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51143"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA five-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parents with a two-day history of fever, vomiting and abdominal pain. He has had several urinary tract infections in the past six months, with worsening symptoms despite antibiotic treatment for each episode. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears uncomfortable. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 39.0\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals tenderness in the right upper quadrant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWhite cell count: 15 x 10^9/L (4.5-13.5)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EC-reactive protein: 80 mg/L (\u003C5)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn ultrasound of the abdomen shows significant progressive hydronephrosis and hydroureter, most noticeable on the right side and more pronounced than on his last ultrasound four months ago. A voiding cystourethrogram (VCUG) reveals dilatation and elongation of the posterior urethra.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause of the recurrent urinary tract infections?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Vesicoureteral reflux","Neurogenic bladder","Duplex kidney","Posterior urethral valves","Ureterocele"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with a history of recurrent urinary tract infections, worsening hydronephrosis on ultrasound, and dilatation and elongation of the posterior urethra on VCUG. These findings are most suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior urethral valves\u003C/strong\u003E. Posterior urethral valves are an obstructing membrane in the posterior male urethra resulting from abnormal in utero development. It is the most common cause of bladder outlet obstruction in male newborns. This obstruction can lead to the development of hydronephrosis (not always bilateral), which increases the risk of urinary tract infections, including pyelonephritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVesicoureteral reflux (VUR)\u003C/strong\u003E is a condition in which urine flows backward from the bladder into the ureters and kidneys. It\u0027s important to note that posterior urethral valves can actually cause secondary VUR due to increased bladder pressure. However, in this case, the primary problem is the urethral obstruction, as evidenced by the VCUG findings of posterior urethral dilatation and elongation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eneurogenic bladder\u003C/strong\u003E is a bladder dysfunction caused by a problem with the nerves that control the bladder. This dysfunction can lead to incomplete bladder emptying, urinary incontinence, and urinary tract infections. However, the history of worsening hydronephrosis on ultrasound and the VCUG findings do not support neurogenic bladder as the primary diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDuplex kidney\u003C/strong\u003E is a congenital anomaly in which the kidney has two separate collecting systems. This condition can increase the risk of urinary tract infections, but the history and imaging findings of this child do not suggest duplex kidney as the underlying cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUreterocele\u003C/strong\u003E is a congenital abnormality found in the ureter. In this condition, the distal ureter balloons at its opening into the bladder, forming a sac-like pouch. This condition can also cause urinary tract obstruction and increase the risk of urinary tract infections, but none of the findings suggest this to be the likely cause here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, the combination of recurrent urinary tract infections, progressive hydronephrosis, and VCUG findings of posterior urethral dilatation and elongation in a male child strongly points to posterior urethral valves as the underlying cause. While this condition can lead to secondary VUR, the primary problem is the urethral obstruction. This condition requires prompt urological evaluation and management to prevent further kidney damage and complications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Progressive hydronephrosis with recurrent UTI in a male child is suggestive of posterior urethral valves.","Posterior urethral valves are the most common cause of bladder outlet obstruction in male newborns.","Voiding cystourethrogram (VCUG) showing dilatation and elongation of the posterior urethra is diagnostic of posterior urethral valves."],"references":["Bingham G, Rentea RM. Posterior Urethral Valve. [Updated 2022 Aug 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36403"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12473"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36403","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36403"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-21T15:52:13+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-21T15:54:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4980"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51143"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"ty